            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5637.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi></ref>, p. 388, CD credited Lynch with calling his attention to the fact that young leaves of <hi rend="italic">Euphorbia jacquiniiflora</hi> Hook. (a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Euphorbia fulgens</hi>, the scarlet plume) slept by hanging vertically downwards. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11139.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to R. I. Lynch, 14 September 1877</ref>.</note>
